<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-245-759  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 245 759.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Jan 9 1989 v23 n1 p55(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Clearing the air. (Taking Charge) (misconceptions in datanormalization) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Pepelea, Michael.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Many MIS executives harbor misconceptions about the benefits ofdata normalization in creating effective data structures whichprevent them from supporting it in their organizations.andP;  MISexecutives will be more inclined to support a data normalizationapproach if their database administration addresses thesemisconceptions.andP;  The misconception that data normalization doesnot address business needs and offers no benefit to the systemdesign process is untrue because although data normalization isbased on user requirements it does not exclude business needs.andO;Another misconception is that data structures produced fromnormalized data models contain too many segments or sets, havelarge access paths, require huge I-O operations and requirecomplex key relationships, but actually performance is better indata-normalized structures because I-O is better controlled anddefined.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Data StructuresModelingMISMethods.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>